{% extends "base.html.jinja" %}

{% block subtitle %}
<p class="subtitle">
  for
  {%- if repo_url %} <a href="{{ repo_url }}">{{ report.input.repo }}</a>
  {%- else %} {{ report.input.repo }}
  {%- endif %} ·
  {{ report.input.start }} → {{ report.input.stop }} ·
  <span class="stamp">generated {{ generated_at.strftime("%Y-%m-%d %H:%M %Z").strip() }}</span>
</p>
{% endblock %}

{# Suppress auto-rendered base sections — they fold into collapsibles below. #}
{% block key_insight %}{% endblock %}
{% block next_actions %}{% endblock %}
{% block caveats %}{% endblock %}
{% block reproduce %}{% endblock %}
{% block vocabulary %}{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
{% if report.result.pr_count == 0 %}
<p>No PRs merged in this window.</p>
{% else %}

{# Headline numbers come from interpretation.headline (rendered by
   base.html.jinja). No restatement here — the per-PR table below
   already carries every individual cycle/active total. #}

{# One-line trust note above the fold. The mechanics live in the
   "How active time is estimated" details below so the headline FE
   stays the dominant signal up top. #}
<p class="trust-note">
  Active time is <em>inferred</em> from event timing on GitHub, not
  measured directly. See <a href="#how-active-time-is-estimated">how
  it's estimated</a> below before treating the number as precise.
</p>

{# Top slowest PRs — the system bottleneck. #}
<h2>Top slowest PRs</h2>
<p class="footnote-wider">
These PRs drove the portfolio's cycle-time tail. Improving any one of
them moves the portfolio number more than improving a typical PR.
</p>
<div>
{% for p in per_pr_by_cycle[:5] %}
  <div class="intervention">
    <span class="id">
      {%- if pr_urls.get(p.item_id) -%}
        <a href="{{ pr_urls[p.item_id] }}">{{ p.item_id }}</a>
      {%- else -%}
        {{ p.item_id }}
      {%- endif -%}
    </span>
    <span class="age">{{ fmt_duration(p.cycle_time) }}</span>
    <span class="state"><span class="pill">FE {{ "%.1f"|format(p.efficiency * 100) }}%</span></span>
    <span class="title">{{ p.title[:90] }}</span>
  </div>
{% endfor %}
</div>

<div id="efficiency-chart" class="chart"></div>
<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/vega@5"></script>
<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/vega-lite@5"></script>
<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/vega-embed@6"></script>
<script>
  vegaEmbed("#efficiency-chart", {{ vega_spec_json | safe }}, {
    actions: {export: true, source: false, compiled: false, editor: false},
    renderer: "svg"
  }).catch(function(err) {
    document.getElementById("efficiency-chart").innerText =
      "Interactive chart failed to render: " + err;
  });
</script>

<p class="footnote-wider">
<strong>Why does the 100% bar look so tall?</strong> A PR scores
100% when every one of its events falls inside a single
{{ report.input.gap_hours }}-hour window — common for typo fixes,
dependency bumps, and bot-authored PRs, where there's no time for a
queue to form. The portfolio number in the headline weights each PR
by its cycle time, so those short PRs don't drag the system number
up the way they drag this bar's count up.
</p>
{% endif %}
{% endblock %}

{% block detail %}
{% if report.result.pr_count > 0 %}
<details>
<summary>Show all {{ per_pr_sorted|length }} PRs (slowest first)</summary>
<table>
<thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Cycle</th><th>Active</th><th>FE</th><th>Title</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
{% for p in per_pr_sorted %}
  <tr>
    <td>
      {%- if pr_urls.get(p.item_id) -%}
        <a href="{{ pr_urls[p.item_id] }}">{{ p.item_id }}</a>
      {%- else -%}
        {{ p.item_id }}
      {%- endif -%}
    </td>
    <td class="num">{{ fmt_duration(p.cycle_time) }}</td>
    <td class="num">{{ fmt_duration(p.active_time) }}</td>
    <td class="num">{{ "%.1f"|format(p.efficiency * 100) }}%</td>
    <td>{{ p.title[:80] }}</td>
  </tr>
{% endfor %}
</tbody>
</table>
</details>
{% endif %}

<details id="how-active-time-is-estimated" open>
<summary>How active time is estimated</summary>
<p>GitHub does not record when a PR is being worked on versus waiting
in review. We infer it from the timing of each PR's events
(commits, reviews, comments, push events). A concrete walk-through:</p>

<p class="walkthrough">
Alice pushes a commit to PR #4 at 8:00 AM Tuesday. She pushes
another to the same PR at 8:55 AM, then a third at 9:30 AM. All
three events are within
<strong>{{ report.input.gap_hours }} hours</strong> of each other,
so they form a single <em>work session</em> on PR #4 — from 8:00 to
9:30 AM, 1.5 hours of <em>active time</em> credited to that PR.
</p>

<p class="walkthrough">
At 9:35 AM Alice switches to PR #3, pushes a commit, and works on
it through the rest of the morning. Because more than
<strong>{{ report.input.gap_hours }} hours</strong> later Alice has
not touched PR #4 again, PR #4's work session is considered closed
at 9:30 AM. The 4-plus hours of clock time between 9:30 AM and her
next event on PR #4 count as <strong>wait time</strong> for PR #4,
not active time — even though Alice was working, she was working on
something else. (If a reviewer comments on PR #4 in that gap, that
counts as a separate work session for PR #4.)
</p>

<p class="walkthrough">
A lone isolated event (e.g. one comment with no surrounding
activity) would otherwise count for zero seconds of active time.
We credit it with at least
<strong>{{ report.input.min_cluster_minutes }} minutes</strong> so a
short review pass isn't recorded as having taken zero work.
</p>

<p class="compact-prose">
Both numbers are tunable: <code>--gap-hours</code> and
<code>--min-cluster-minutes</code>. The defaults
({{ report.input.gap_hours }}h /
{{ report.input.min_cluster_minutes }} min) are reasonable for
solo-author-plus-async-review patterns; teams that pair-program or
swarm a PR may want a higher gap; teams with very frequent commits
may want a lower one. Raising the gap raises FE; lowering it lowers
FE.
</p>
</details>

<details>
<summary>Reproduce this report</summary>
<table>
  <tr><th>Repo</th><td>{{ report.input.repo }}</td></tr>
  <tr><th>Window</th><td>{{ report.input.start }} → {{ report.input.stop }}</td></tr>
  <tr><th>Active-time gap</th><td>{{ report.input.gap_hours }}h</td></tr>
  <tr><th>Min cluster</th><td>{{ report.input.min_cluster_minutes }}min</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="invocation">{{ invocation }}</div>
</details>

<details>
<summary>About this report</summary>
<p><strong>What this shows.</strong> {{ definition }}</p>

{# The "How active time was calculated" prose moved into its own
   details block above ("How active time is estimated") with a
   concrete Alice walk-through. Don't restate it here. #}

{% if report.result.pr_count > 0 %}
<p><strong>Median vs. mean per-PR FE.</strong> A simple average of
each PR's FE is biased upward by the long tail of small fast PRs (a
single 5-minute typo fix scores 100% and pulls the mean up). The
median tells you what a typical PR looks like in isolation, which
is a different question from "how efficient is our system overall".
For decisions about where wait time is leaking, use the portfolio
number in the headline; these two are listed for completeness.</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Median per-PR FE</th><td class="num">{{ "%.1f"|format(report.result.median_efficiency * 100) }}%</td></tr>
  <tr><th>Mean per-PR FE</th><td class="num">{{ "%.1f"|format(report.result.mean_efficiency * 100) }}%</td></tr>
</table>
{% endif %}

{% if interpretation.key_insight %}
<p><strong>Key insight.</strong> {{ interpretation.key_insight }}</p>
{% endif %}

{% if interpretation.next_actions %}
<p><strong>Next actions</strong></p>
<ol class="compact-prose">
{% for action in interpretation.next_actions %}
  <li>{{ action }}</li>
{% endfor %}
</ol>
{% endif %}

{% if interpretation.caveats %}
<p><strong>Caveats</strong></p>
<ul class="footnote-wider">
{% for c in interpretation.caveats %}
  <li>{{ c }}</li>
{% endfor %}
</ul>
{% endif %}

<p><strong>Vocabulary</strong></p>
<dl>
{% for term, defn in vocabulary.items() %}
  <dt><strong>{{ term }}</strong></dt>
  <dd>{{ defn }}</dd>
{% endfor %}
</dl>
</details>
{% endblock %}
